1
00:00:18,239 --> 00:00:22,784
# <i>Bach "Toccata and Fugue in D minor"</i>

2
00:03:11,493 --> 00:03:13,071
<i>(engines rev)</i>

3
00:03:27,850 --> 00:03:29,595
<i>(cheering)</i>

4
00:03:29,728 --> 00:03:33,395
(announcer) <i>Good evening.</i>
<i>Welcome to Houston, the Energy City...</i>

5
00:03:33,525 --> 00:03:36,777
<i>... home of the defending rollerball</i>
<i>world champions.</i>

6
00:03:36,905 --> 00:03:40,608
<i>This key international battle</i>
<i>pits divisional champions Madrid...</i>

7
00:03:40,744 --> 00:03:42,785
<i>... against powerful Houston.</i>

8
00:03:44,834 --> 00:03:46,874
<i>(engines rev)</i>

9
00:03:57,727 --> 00:04:00,398
<i>And here they come for a standing ovation.</i>

10
00:04:00,523 --> 00:04:02,517
<i>On the track comes Houston!</i>

11
00:04:02,651 --> 00:04:05,440
<i>Houston, led by captain Jonathan E...</i>

12
00:04:05,572 --> 00:04:08,029
<i>... again their leading scorer this year.</i>

13
00:04:08,159 --> 00:04:11,078
<i>(crowd chants)</i> Jonathan! Jonathan!

14
00:04:26,102 --> 00:04:28,476
OK. Let's go.

15
00:04:39,998 --> 00:04:42,455
<i>The controller indicates that he is ready...</i>

16
00:04:42,585 --> 00:04:46,038
<i>... and our 30 Multivision cameras</i>
<i>will bring you all the speed...</i>

17
00:04:46,174 --> 00:04:48,547
<i>... thrills and excitement of this critical game.</i>

18
00:04:48,677 --> 00:04:52,095
(announcer #2) <i>Ladies and gentlemen,</i>
<i>our corporate anthem.</i>

19
00:04:56,105 --> 00:04:58,775
<i>(organ music)</i>

20
00:06:11,549 --> 00:06:13,589
<i>(cheering)</i>

21
00:06:19,060 --> 00:06:23,225
<i>The controller tests his equipment,</i>
<i>readies for the start of game action.</i>

22
00:06:23,358 --> 00:06:27,310
<i>The traditional firing of the test ball</i>
<i>will signal we're about set to go.</i>

23
00:06:27,447 --> 00:06:29,357
<i>(klaxon)</i>

24
00:06:30,076 --> 00:06:32,651
(announcer #2)
<i>The controller for tonight's game...</i>

25
00:06:32,788 --> 00:06:35,411
<i>... DA Niehaus.</i>

26
00:06:35,542 --> 00:06:39,542
(announcer #1) <i>The officials approve play.</i>
<i>Each team concludes its huddle...</i>

27
00:06:39,673 --> 00:06:44,136
<i>... and now the crowd cheers once again as</i>
<i>this Houston audience greets its team...</i>

28
00:06:44,264 --> 00:06:46,506
<i>... led by the stalwart athlete Jonathan E.</i>

29
00:06:48,728 --> 00:06:51,185
Break off. That's it, boys.

30
00:06:51,316 --> 00:06:52,692
Hook it!

31
00:06:52,818 --> 00:06:56,271
<i>(crowd chants)</i> Houston! Houston! Houston!

32
00:06:56,406 --> 00:06:58,696
Houston! Houston!

33
00:06:59,035 --> 00:07:01,076
Houston! Houston!

34
00:07:01,414 --> 00:07:03,787
Houston! Houston!

35
00:07:15,100 --> 00:07:18,518
<i>Now the play-by-play. Here's RD.</i>

36
00:07:20,066 --> 00:07:22,903
(RD) <i>The computer counts down.</i>
<i>The ball is fired.</i>

37
00:07:23,029 --> 00:07:25,699
<i>First period is under way</i>
<i>here at Houston tonight.</i>

38
00:07:26,868 --> 00:07:30,072
<i>The first team</i>
<i>to pick up the ball will be on offence...</i>

39
00:07:30,206 --> 00:07:32,877
<i>... as they try for a score,</i>
<i>and it's a pick-up by Houston!</i>

40
00:07:33,002 --> 00:07:35,161
<i>BJ moves around the track...</i>

41
00:07:35,297 --> 00:07:37,456
<i>... manoeuvring it in to the leading scorer...</i>

42
00:07:37,592 --> 00:07:39,585
- <i>... Jonathan E.</i>
- Go on! Go on!

43
00:07:39,720 --> 00:07:41,760
Watch him!

44
00:07:46,647 --> 00:07:50,896
<i>Jonathan E holds the ball aloft.</i>
<i>You must hold it in plain view at all times.</i>

45
00:07:51,028 --> 00:07:54,862
- Pick 'em up, pick 'em up!
- I got it, I got it.

46
00:07:54,992 --> 00:07:56,653
On your right!

47
00:07:59,499 --> 00:08:03,201
<i>Jonathan moves in behind</i>
<i>and then out in front of Blue's bike.</i>

48
00:08:03,338 --> 00:08:06,376
<i>Jonathan moves up the track</i>
<i>and up onto the side.</i>

49
00:08:06,509 --> 00:08:09,465
<i>Here comes Sanchez.</i>
<i>Sanchez grabs Jonathan...</i>

50
00:08:09,597 --> 00:08:13,431
<i>... but off the rail comes Moonpie</i>
<i>and takes out four Madrid men.</i>

51
00:08:13,561 --> 00:08:16,018
<i>The old swooper Moonpie...</i>

52
00:08:16,148 --> 00:08:20,018
<i>... came right off the top of the rail</i>
<i>and took out four Madrid men.</i>

53
00:08:21,907 --> 00:08:25,159
<i>The remaining Madrid skaters</i>
<i>defend the front of the goal.</i>

54
00:08:25,287 --> 00:08:26,663
<i>Jonathan still has the ball.</i>

55
00:08:26,789 --> 00:08:29,791
<i>Moving in, he'll try to shoot.</i>
<i>He does! Jonathan!</i>

56
00:08:29,919 --> 00:08:31,793
<i>He shoots, and it's just wide.</i>

57
00:08:31,922 --> 00:08:33,085
Regroup!

58
00:08:33,215 --> 00:08:35,375
<i>The Houston team will have to regroup.</i>

59
00:08:35,510 --> 00:08:39,640
<i>Injured on the play is Belmonte</i>
<i>and he's helped off the track for Madrid.</i>

60
00:08:39,766 --> 00:08:43,386
<i>First period, no score, as we get set</i>
<i>for the firing of the second ball.</i>

61
00:08:52,160 --> 00:08:54,652
<i>Oh, and he misses</i>
<i>and it hits the bike of Carter.</i>

62
00:08:54,788 --> 00:08:56,829
<i>Knocks Carter down.</i>

63
00:08:57,376 --> 00:08:59,416
Gimme a hand. Move out!

64
00:09:14,192 --> 00:09:17,942
<i>Jonathan is there. It is handed off.</i>
<i>The pass is complete to Jonathan.</i>

65
00:09:18,073 --> 00:09:19,318
<i>(chanting)</i>

66
00:09:27,211 --> 00:09:29,086
<i>He skates by and knocks him down dead!</i>

67
00:09:29,214 --> 00:09:30,377
Did you see that?

68
00:09:30,508 --> 00:09:33,426
<i>That should be a penalty.</i>
<i>The official looking over.</i>

69
00:09:33,554 --> 00:09:35,761
<i>Moonpie skates by as if nothing happened.</i>

70
00:09:35,890 --> 00:09:37,469
Keep up!

71
00:09:37,601 --> 00:09:40,687
- Moon, on your left, on your left.
- Right, right!

72
00:09:40,814 --> 00:09:43,307
- Take him out!
- I got him.

73
00:09:47,741 --> 00:09:49,782
Break it up, break it up!

74
00:09:49,911 --> 00:09:51,821
Go, Jonathan, go!

75
00:09:51,956 --> 00:09:54,662
<i>Can he give Houston</i>
<i>the first goal of the game?</i>

76
00:09:54,793 --> 00:09:57,166
- <i>He shoots, he scores!</i>
- Yeah!

77
00:09:57,297 --> 00:10:00,050
<i>And at the end of the first period...</i>

78
00:10:00,176 --> 00:10:03,926
<i>... Jonathan's goal gives Houston</i>
<i>a 1-0 lead over Madrid.</i>

79
00:10:04,057 --> 00:10:10,394
(announcer #2) <i>Scored by Jonathan E!</i>
<i>The time - first period, 12 minutes.</i>

80
00:10:11,276 --> 00:10:13,103
<i>(klaxon)</i>

81
00:10:14,989 --> 00:10:18,075
(RD) <i>The ball is fired</i>
<i>for the start of the second period.</i>

82
00:10:18,203 --> 00:10:20,077
<i>Madrid, trailing by one goal...</i>

83
00:10:20,205 --> 00:10:23,410
<i>... try to go on offence to tie the score.</i>

84
00:10:25,255 --> 00:10:26,631
Go, Madrid!

85
00:10:29,678 --> 00:10:33,428
- Here, latch on, latch on.
- I'm with you.

86
00:10:33,558 --> 00:10:35,552
Come on, Madrid, come on!

87
00:10:35,687 --> 00:10:39,140
<i>He skates up in front.</i>
<i>Gonzales still has it for Madrid.</i>

88
00:10:39,275 --> 00:10:41,269
<i>Hands off again, this time to Bodeus.</i>

89
00:10:41,403 --> 00:10:44,988
<i>Bodeus, on offence for the Madrid team.</i>

90
00:10:45,117 --> 00:10:46,945
<i>Here's the Houston defence.</i>

91
00:10:47,078 --> 00:10:50,365
<i>It's a shot. It's low!</i>
<i>And back down to the track goes Bodeus.</i>

92
00:10:50,500 --> 00:10:53,538
<i>He's not injured,</i>
<i>but his scoring attempt failed.</i>

93
00:10:53,671 --> 00:10:56,876
<i>And the score is still 1-0 in favour of Houston.</i>

94
00:10:57,009 --> 00:10:59,584
<i>The ball is fired again.</i>
<i>Madrid is pressing now.</i>

95
00:10:59,722 --> 00:11:00,802
<i>Putting the pressure on.</i>

96
00:11:00,932 --> 00:11:03,555
Move it! Come on, move!

97
00:11:05,772 --> 00:11:07,896
Hold on. Come on, let's move it!

98
00:11:08,401 --> 00:11:10,395
We got it now.

99
00:11:10,529 --> 00:11:12,523
Hold on, hold on.

100
00:11:12,657 --> 00:11:14,532
Watch it. Keep an eye out!

101
00:11:14,660 --> 00:11:16,286
<i>(fast handclapping)</i>

102
00:11:17,206 --> 00:11:19,246
<i>Coming in now, Sanchez.</i>

103
00:11:19,376 --> 00:11:21,416
<i>Moving to his left and right.</i>

104
00:11:21,546 --> 00:11:24,085
<i>Has a full head of steam, still on offence...</i>

105
00:11:24,216 --> 00:11:27,302
<i>... trying to tie the score.</i>
<i>Sanchez moves around the bike...</i>

106
00:11:27,429 --> 00:11:29,719
<i>... takes a long looping shot. He scores!</i>

107
00:11:29,849 --> 00:11:32,342
<i>Sanchez scores for Madrid</i>
<i>and ties the game...</i>

108
00:11:32,478 --> 00:11:33,854
<i>... 1-1.</i>

109
00:11:33,980 --> 00:11:35,012
<i>Second period.</i>

110
00:11:35,149 --> 00:11:39,231
<i>The ball is in play again,</i>
<i>and scooped up this time by Aston!</i>

111
00:11:42,994 --> 00:11:45,283
Three minutes. Get off!

112
00:11:45,414 --> 00:11:46,909
- <i>(klaxon)</i>
- <i>Madrid penalty.</i>

113
00:11:47,041 --> 00:11:50,079
<i>Three minutes. Biking misconduct.</i>

114
00:11:50,213 --> 00:11:52,253
<i>On No.1 biker.</i>

115
00:11:56,180 --> 00:11:57,176
<i>(klaxon)</i>

116
00:11:57,306 --> 00:12:00,143
Are you satisfied, Madrid?
What game are you guys playing?

117
00:12:12,454 --> 00:12:15,955
Take it easy. Take it easy.
Relax, you'll be all right.

118
00:12:16,084 --> 00:12:18,077
<i>The crowd's going wild...</i>

119
00:12:18,212 --> 00:12:23,042
<i>... loving this wide-open action</i>
<i>in this quarterfinal game.</i>

120
00:12:23,178 --> 00:12:25,848
Skate! Skate! Come on, goddammit, skate!

121
00:12:28,811 --> 00:12:30,721
Houston! Houston! Houston!

122
00:12:34,820 --> 00:12:37,822
<i>They all go down, a pile-up on the track.</i>

123
00:12:37,949 --> 00:12:41,616
<i>The ball rolls free,</i>
<i>and into the gutter. It's a dead ball.</i>

124
00:12:41,747 --> 00:12:42,743
<i>(klaxon)</i>

125
00:12:42,873 --> 00:12:46,955
Here, here, here! Come on, come on!
Off the track, off the track!

126
00:12:47,088 --> 00:12:49,128
Come on, move out!

127
00:12:52,095 --> 00:12:53,554
How is it, Jonathan?

128
00:12:54,307 --> 00:12:56,715
- Give me a towel, will you, Bull?
- Sure.

129
00:12:56,852 --> 00:12:58,263
<i>(coughs)</i>

130
00:13:01,442 --> 00:13:03,067
Come on, Dune!

131
00:13:13,126 --> 00:13:15,166
<i>Moonpie drop-kicks him!</i>

132
00:13:15,296 --> 00:13:17,336
<i>(booing)</i>

133
00:13:17,466 --> 00:13:19,506
Three-minute penalty!

134
00:13:20,804 --> 00:13:23,510
Don't give me any of that. Off the track!

135
00:13:33,489 --> 00:13:35,364
Group up.

136
00:13:37,912 --> 00:13:40,831
<i>Jumping over the Madrid defence,</i>
<i>gets up in front of the goal...</i>

137
00:13:40,958 --> 00:13:43,830
<i>... and he jams it in for the score!</i>

138
00:13:43,963 --> 00:13:46,372
<i>Jonathan jams it in and scores...</i>

139
00:13:46,508 --> 00:13:49,345
<i>... to give Houston a 2-1 lead over Madrid.</i>

140
00:13:49,471 --> 00:13:51,429
<i>Houston with the ball again.</i>

141
00:13:51,557 --> 00:13:53,598
- <i>Here in the third...</i>
- It's a bike!

142
00:13:56,523 --> 00:13:59,359
- Stop him!
- <i>(klaxon)</i>

143
00:14:05,286 --> 00:14:07,659
<i>Jonathan E has it.</i>
<i>Jonathan coming in low...</i>

144
00:14:07,789 --> 00:14:11,741
<i>... with a great manoeuvre.</i>
<i>He shoots, he scores!</i>

145
00:14:13,631 --> 00:14:15,672
I love this game, Moonpie.

146
00:14:15,801 --> 00:14:17,047
- I love it.
- Yeah!

147
00:14:17,721 --> 00:14:19,761
Jonathan! Jonathan!

148
00:14:24,022 --> 00:14:26,478
Two games left.
Guess who we're playing first.

149
00:14:26,609 --> 00:14:30,858
Tokyo. Ha-ha! Who'd have thought
they'd make it to the play-off?

150
00:14:30,990 --> 00:14:33,827
They're good.
They've got the old Samurai spirit.

151
00:14:33,953 --> 00:14:36,160
Yeah, but they're all about this tall.

152
00:14:36,290 --> 00:14:38,960
Two or three little things make one big thing.

153
00:14:39,085 --> 00:14:42,171
They're liable to climb all over you
and eat your lunch!

154
00:14:42,298 --> 00:14:46,797
I can't get on a man-to-man basis
with a pygmy or an Oriental.

155
00:14:46,930 --> 00:14:48,722
I don't know what it is.

156
00:14:54,984 --> 00:14:57,654
You were fine tonight, all of you.

157
00:14:58,864 --> 00:14:59,896
Mean...

158
00:15:00,033 --> 00:15:02,157
...sharp!
- Thank you.

159
00:15:02,286 --> 00:15:05,372
- You fellas did well again.
- Thank you, Mr Bartholomew.

160
00:15:05,499 --> 00:15:08,336
And you, you rolled, you really rolled.

161
00:15:08,462 --> 00:15:09,458
Yeah.

162
00:15:09,589 --> 00:15:13,041
You play like our champion here.
You take lessons from him?

163
00:15:13,177 --> 00:15:15,467
No, we just give lessons to the other team!

164
00:15:15,597 --> 00:15:17,390
<i>(clapping)</i>

165
00:15:17,517 --> 00:15:18,846
How are you, Jonathan?

166
00:15:18,977 --> 00:15:22,430
I'm, uh, feeling mean, Mr Bartholomew.
It's good to see you.

167
00:15:22,566 --> 00:15:25,521
Jonathan E, that's the name.

168
00:15:26,780 --> 00:15:29,902
Houston players come and go,
but the champion...

169
00:15:30,035 --> 00:15:32,362
...plays on.

170
00:15:32,497 --> 00:15:33,328
Hear, hear!

171
00:15:33,457 --> 00:15:37,955
The Energy Corporation has a hard time
figuring out ways to pay the champion.

172
00:15:38,089 --> 00:15:40,663
We can't think up any more rewards for him.

173
00:15:40,801 --> 00:15:43,008
You'd like us to have that problem with you?

174
00:15:43,138 --> 00:15:44,134
Yes, sir!

175
00:15:44,557 --> 00:15:47,844
You're like Jonathan,
you play with abandon...

176
00:15:47,978 --> 00:15:50,815
...but this is Jonathan's season.

177
00:15:51,609 --> 00:15:53,851
Every season seems to be
Jonathan's season...

178
00:15:53,987 --> 00:15:57,239
...but this year we've got you
on Multivision...

179
00:15:57,367 --> 00:15:59,610
...a special show all about you.

180
00:15:59,745 --> 00:16:02,617
No player ever had that before.

181
00:16:02,750 --> 00:16:06,536
The whole world will be watching
because this is your year.

182
00:16:06,672 --> 00:16:08,298
<i>(cheering)</i>

183
00:16:08,634 --> 00:16:09,630
You got it, babe!

184
00:16:13,724 --> 00:16:16,892
- So, two games left.
- That's right, Mr Bartholomew.

185
00:16:17,021 --> 00:16:19,061
New York in the final!

186
00:16:21,945 --> 00:16:23,985
The team seems healthy...

187
00:16:24,115 --> 00:16:27,070
...the champion says he feels mean.

188
00:16:27,828 --> 00:16:29,869
No problems here.

189
00:16:29,998 --> 00:16:32,039
That's right!

190
00:16:32,961 --> 00:16:35,001
What is this, fruit juice?

191
00:16:35,131 --> 00:16:38,252
Very healthy, Mr Bartholomew. Very healthy.

192
00:16:46,898 --> 00:16:49,355
Sweet dreams, Moonpie.

193
00:16:49,944 --> 00:16:52,187
It's a bad habit you've got there.

194
00:16:53,282 --> 00:16:57,068
You know what that habit
will make you dream, Moonpie?

195
00:16:57,205 --> 00:16:59,744
You'll dream you're an executive.

196
00:17:00,543 --> 00:17:03,214
You'll have your hands on all the controls...

197
00:17:03,339 --> 00:17:07,125
...and you'll wear a grey suit,
and you'll make decisions.

198
00:17:07,261 --> 00:17:09,136
But you know what, Moonpie?

199
00:17:09,264 --> 00:17:12,183
You know what those executives
dream about...

200
00:17:12,310 --> 00:17:14,518
...out there behind their desks?

201
00:17:14,647 --> 00:17:17,982
They dream they're great rollerballers.

202
00:17:18,110 --> 00:17:21,861
They dream they're Jonathan.
They have muscles.

203
00:17:21,991 --> 00:17:24,614
- They bash in faces.
- <i>(all)</i> Yeah!

204
00:17:26,706 --> 00:17:29,578
Are we ready to go?
Can't keep these boys here all night.

205
00:17:29,711 --> 00:17:30,660
Jonathan...

206
00:17:30,796 --> 00:17:33,039
...come and see me, tomorrow.

207
00:17:36,346 --> 00:17:38,802
Good night, Mr Bartholomew.

208
00:17:39,433 --> 00:17:42,638
- Ssh! Quiet, quiet.
- This is a great team.

209
00:17:42,772 --> 00:17:44,812
A great city.

210
00:17:44,983 --> 00:17:47,226
Great stuff out there tonight.

211
00:17:47,362 --> 00:17:49,402
<i>(cheering)</i>

212
00:18:07,099 --> 00:18:09,140
<i>(crowd cheers)</i>

213
00:18:16,863 --> 00:18:20,364
<i>(crowd chants)</i>
Jonathan! Jonathan! Jonathan! Jonathan!

214
00:18:20,494 --> 00:18:23,995
Jonathan! Jonathan! Jonathan! Jonathan!

215
00:18:24,124 --> 00:18:26,581
Jonathan! Jonathan! Jonathan!

216
00:18:34,264 --> 00:18:35,889
<i>(screaming)</i>

217
00:18:36,350 --> 00:18:39,056
<i>(crowd chants)</i>
Jonathan! Jonathan! Jonathan!

218
00:18:39,188 --> 00:18:43,401
Jonathan! Jonathan! Jonathan! Jonathan!

219
00:18:46,866 --> 00:18:49,536
Jonathan! Jonathan! Jonathan!

220
00:18:49,870 --> 00:18:52,362
Jonathan! Jonathan! Jonathan!

221
00:18:52,708 --> 00:18:55,282
Jonathan! Jonathan! Jonathan!

222
00:19:31,181 --> 00:19:32,973
- Good morning.
- How are you?

223
00:19:33,100 --> 00:19:35,343
- Brutal game last night.
- Thank you.

224
00:19:35,479 --> 00:19:38,980
- So it's Tokyo in the semifinals?
- That's right.

225
00:19:44,617 --> 00:19:47,406
Continue to hold the calls, all right?

226
00:20:09,696 --> 00:20:11,523
Come in, Jonathan.

227
00:20:11,657 --> 00:20:14,410
Keep silence with me
for a minute, won't you?

228
00:20:15,955 --> 00:20:17,580
<i>(chiming)</i>

229
00:20:52,967 --> 00:20:56,670
It's important to have a place
to think things out.

230
00:20:56,806 --> 00:21:01,435
You have your ranch.
I know you take a lot of pleasure in it.

231
00:21:01,563 --> 00:21:03,557
I, uh, cut my finger.

232
00:21:03,692 --> 00:21:06,148
I'm sorry. Here.

233
00:21:09,241 --> 00:21:12,197
You've had an amazing career, Jonathan.

234
00:21:12,496 --> 00:21:15,498
You know how proud we are
of the Houston team...

235
00:21:15,626 --> 00:21:18,747
...and what we think of you... at Energy.

236
00:21:19,965 --> 00:21:22,884
But now there are executives
who want you out.

237
00:21:23,012 --> 00:21:24,554
Sir?

238
00:21:24,681 --> 00:21:27,434
You've had 10 years in this game, Jonathan...

239
00:21:27,560 --> 00:21:29,600
...Ionger than anyone ever.

240
00:21:30,230 --> 00:21:32,271
Retire... How can I do that?

241
00:21:32,400 --> 00:21:34,774
On your special programme.

242
00:21:34,904 --> 00:21:38,904
There are some who feel that
this programme should now be used to...

243
00:21:39,035 --> 00:21:41,076
...announce your retirement.

244
00:21:41,205 --> 00:21:42,830
Who wants that?

245
00:21:42,957 --> 00:21:46,079
When this special was first planned
by us here at Energy...

246
00:21:46,212 --> 00:21:48,455
...we saw it as a good thing...

247
00:21:48,841 --> 00:21:51,879
...but now the Executive Directorate
wants a change.

248
00:21:52,012 --> 00:21:55,715
The programme is scheduled,
the whole world is waiting for it...

249
00:21:55,851 --> 00:21:59,388
...so this does seem the perfect time.

250
00:22:00,441 --> 00:22:02,269
The, um, team...

251
00:22:02,403 --> 00:22:04,443
They, uh, they depend on me.

252
00:22:04,573 --> 00:22:07,575
Jonathan, let's think this through together.

253
00:22:07,702 --> 00:22:10,574
You know how the game serves us.

254
00:22:11,750 --> 00:22:14,622
It has a definite social purpose.

255
00:22:14,963 --> 00:22:17,882
Nations are bankrupt, gone.

256
00:22:18,635 --> 00:22:21,507
None of that tribal warfare any more.

257
00:22:22,015 --> 00:22:25,432
Even the corporate wars
are a thing of the past.

258
00:22:25,937 --> 00:22:27,978
Yeah, well, I know that. It's just...

259
00:22:28,107 --> 00:22:31,228
So now we have the majors
and their executives.

260
00:22:31,362 --> 00:22:34,234
Transport, food, communication...

261
00:22:34,617 --> 00:22:37,489
...housing, luxury, energy.

262
00:22:38,205 --> 00:22:42,074
A few of us making decisions
on a global basis...

263
00:22:42,211 --> 00:22:43,671
...for the common good.

264
00:22:43,797 --> 00:22:47,001
The team is a unit.
It plays with certain rhythms.

265
00:22:47,135 --> 00:22:49,841
So does an executive team, Jonathan.

266
00:22:50,056 --> 00:22:52,727
Now everyone has all the comforts...

267
00:22:52,852 --> 00:22:54,263
...you know that.

268
00:22:54,396 --> 00:22:56,970
No poverty, no sickness.

269
00:22:57,108 --> 00:22:59,779
No needs and many luxuries...

270
00:22:59,904 --> 00:23:03,986
...which you enjoy just as if
you were in the executive class.

271
00:23:04,118 --> 00:23:07,453
Corporate society takes care of everything.

272
00:23:08,166 --> 00:23:09,958
And all it asks of anyone...

273
00:23:10,085 --> 00:23:13,372
...all it has ever asked of anyone ever...

274
00:23:13,507 --> 00:23:16,426
...is not to interfere
with management decisions.

275
00:23:16,553 --> 00:23:20,422
I, uh... I don't mean to resist.

276
00:23:20,726 --> 00:23:22,351
I'm just trying to understand.

277
00:23:22,479 --> 00:23:27,107
This is for your own benefit.
You must know that, Jonathan.

278
00:23:27,236 --> 00:23:29,858
All decisions concerning you are.

279
00:23:31,742 --> 00:23:33,617
Well, I, uh...

280
00:23:33,745 --> 00:23:35,703
I lost Ella.

281
00:23:35,831 --> 00:23:38,039
The Corporation took my wife away...

282
00:23:38,168 --> 00:23:41,420
...because an executive wanted her.
- I won't review all that.

283
00:23:41,548 --> 00:23:44,301
That was before I took over.
I had nothing to do with it.

284
00:23:44,427 --> 00:23:48,213
From what I hear
your wife wanted to leave herself.

285
00:23:48,350 --> 00:23:51,851
So, now, you're going to retire.

286
00:23:52,731 --> 00:23:55,270
That shouldn't be too hard for you.

287
00:23:55,736 --> 00:23:57,860
Stupid game, after all.

288
00:23:57,989 --> 00:24:01,775
Awful game.
You ought to be glad to be out of it.

289
00:24:04,791 --> 00:24:06,831
I don't, uh...

290
00:24:07,628 --> 00:24:11,414
I don't know, Mr Bartholomew.
I just don't... know.

291
00:24:11,884 --> 00:24:14,756
I realise you had nothing to do
with Ella leaving me.

292
00:24:14,889 --> 00:24:17,844
- Jonathan, I...
- But, um...

293
00:24:18,936 --> 00:24:20,681
I... You're right.

294
00:24:20,814 --> 00:24:23,057
I mean, uh, I ought to do...

295
00:24:23,568 --> 00:24:26,239
I ought to be perfectly happy
to do what you say.

296
00:24:26,364 --> 00:24:29,651
Take your time. Take a few days.

297
00:24:30,871 --> 00:24:34,288
You've just come through a game.
You're tired.

298
00:24:34,459 --> 00:24:38,411
Go to your ranch, but... think about it.

299
00:24:38,882 --> 00:24:41,339
And understand it.

300
00:24:41,845 --> 00:24:44,302
Do understand it.

301
00:25:04,211 --> 00:25:07,297
Because I don't understand your resistance.

302
00:25:07,424 --> 00:25:10,095
And I don't think anyone else will either.

303
00:26:07,304 --> 00:26:09,630
- Was your flight OK?
- Is Clete here?

304
00:26:09,766 --> 00:26:12,852
- He's in the training room.
- I'll go say hello.

305
00:26:14,022 --> 00:26:15,647
Jonathan?

306
00:26:17,235 --> 00:26:19,394
Look what I got for breakfast.

307
00:26:19,989 --> 00:26:22,481
It's a notice from the Corporation.

308
00:26:22,618 --> 00:26:24,493
What's it say?

309
00:26:24,621 --> 00:26:29,332
Oh, that I should, uh, get out of here.
You know, go away, vanish.

310
00:26:29,461 --> 00:26:33,508
That kind of thing.
You know anything about that?

311
00:26:35,345 --> 00:26:38,217
Yeah, I kinda heard something about it.

312
00:26:38,600 --> 00:26:40,640
You knew it was coming.

313
00:26:42,939 --> 00:26:45,610
We've been together six months.

314
00:26:47,613 --> 00:26:50,152
Didn't you even wanna say goodbye?

315
00:26:51,953 --> 00:26:53,911
We'll talk about it later, OK?

316
00:26:54,039 --> 00:26:56,080
You didn't, did you?

317
00:26:56,209 --> 00:26:57,834
Hm?

318
00:26:59,130 --> 00:27:01,800
You didn't even want me here
when you got back.

319
00:27:01,926 --> 00:27:03,634
I gotta go see Cletus.

320
00:27:03,762 --> 00:27:05,969
What do you want me to do in the meantime?

321
00:27:06,098 --> 00:27:07,724
I want you to take it easy.

322
00:27:07,851 --> 00:27:09,476
Uh...

323
00:27:11,064 --> 00:27:13,983
I want you to go in and, uh,
fix us something to eat.

324
00:27:14,110 --> 00:27:16,947
Clete's come a long way
and, uh, I'm hungry...

325
00:27:17,073 --> 00:27:19,031
...all right?

326
00:27:26,003 --> 00:27:27,201
Jonathan?

327
00:27:29,591 --> 00:27:31,964
I'm glad you're all right.

328
00:27:36,768 --> 00:27:38,726
Huh! Huh! Huh!

329
00:27:38,855 --> 00:27:41,477
<i>(punches bag)</i>

330
00:27:41,609 --> 00:27:43,234
Huh!

331
00:27:46,908 --> 00:27:49,282
Come on. All right, come on.

332
00:27:49,412 --> 00:27:51,204
<i>(pats bag)</i>

333
00:27:51,331 --> 00:27:53,372
Come on.

334
00:27:57,340 --> 00:28:00,296
- I ain't tired enough.
- Yeah!

335
00:28:10,568 --> 00:28:12,193
Huh!

336
00:28:15,534 --> 00:28:17,777
Huh! It caught you, didn't it, baby?

337
00:28:17,912 --> 00:28:20,036
- Two games running?
- What?

338
00:28:20,165 --> 00:28:23,702
You did that the last two games.
Shoulder forward left.

339
00:28:23,837 --> 00:28:26,127
You're standing on your left skate.

340
00:28:26,258 --> 00:28:29,960
You do that in Tokyo,
they'll take your arm home for lunch.

341
00:28:30,097 --> 00:28:32,137
You with me?

342
00:28:33,393 --> 00:28:36,064
OK, you practise that for me a little, huh?

343
00:28:36,189 --> 00:28:37,684
All right.

344
00:28:39,026 --> 00:28:40,190
<i>(laughs)</i>

345
00:28:45,160 --> 00:28:48,448
<i>(Cletus)</i> Hell, I forget
which corporation is which.

346
00:28:48,582 --> 00:28:51,039
Any ass knows that fire's energy.

347
00:28:52,421 --> 00:28:54,462
Who wrote the music?

348
00:28:54,591 --> 00:28:56,631
Where does the music come from?

349
00:28:56,969 --> 00:28:58,797
Huh...

350
00:28:58,931 --> 00:29:02,266
- OK if I have one of these?
- Go on, have a holiday.

351
00:29:13,911 --> 00:29:16,997
I forget what corporation's
running what city.

352
00:29:19,002 --> 00:29:21,672
Chicago's still the Food City...

353
00:29:23,091 --> 00:29:26,877
...but what about Indianapolis?
Whatever happened to that town?

354
00:29:27,014 --> 00:29:29,054
Whatever happened to Mackie?

355
00:29:29,851 --> 00:29:32,522
Everything was much simpler
when I was a kid.

356
00:29:32,647 --> 00:29:34,687
We still had three nations.

357
00:29:34,817 --> 00:29:38,270
That was before the corporate wars,
even before rollerball.

358
00:29:38,405 --> 00:29:41,527
Before everything. Do you believe in kids?

359
00:29:41,660 --> 00:29:44,366
I remember someone telling me about...

360
00:29:44,498 --> 00:29:47,369
...the National Football League
and the World Cup.

361
00:29:47,502 --> 00:29:50,338
- Where are you going?
- Indianapolis.

362
00:29:54,053 --> 00:29:56,724
What do you know about that stuff, Clete?

363
00:29:56,849 --> 00:29:58,889
I mean...

364
00:29:59,019 --> 00:30:03,268
...you know, how the Corporations
got started, about the corporate wars.

365
00:30:03,692 --> 00:30:05,852
They were nasty... Phew!

366
00:30:05,987 --> 00:30:08,028
Well, nobody talks about that.

367
00:30:08,157 --> 00:30:11,029
- Well... except for friends.
- Yeah... <i>(laughs)</i>

368
00:30:11,162 --> 00:30:14,283
I remember your rookie year.

369
00:30:14,792 --> 00:30:16,999
You were mean and tight.

370
00:30:17,129 --> 00:30:19,169
The best player I ever coached.

371
00:30:19,716 --> 00:30:23,086
Nobody could lay a hand on you
that year. Remember?

372
00:30:23,221 --> 00:30:25,096
Yeah. Uh...

373
00:30:25,224 --> 00:30:27,264
Look, I gotta ask you something.

374
00:30:27,394 --> 00:30:29,933
That figures. Go ahead, I'm listening.

375
00:30:30,190 --> 00:30:34,106
Well, there's something
going on with the game.

376
00:30:35,531 --> 00:30:39,233
I don't know what it is.
I don't think I'm supposed to know.

377
00:30:39,704 --> 00:30:41,364
What's that?

378
00:30:41,498 --> 00:30:43,741
They want me to quit.

379
00:30:52,264 --> 00:30:55,301
Why... would they want you to do that?

380
00:30:55,435 --> 00:30:57,475
I don't know.

381
00:30:58,147 --> 00:31:00,437
That's what I'd like you to find out.

382
00:31:00,693 --> 00:31:02,733
Well, I'll try.

383
00:31:02,863 --> 00:31:06,696
I hear just about everything going on
in the game, one way or another.

384
00:31:06,827 --> 00:31:11,040
That's what I mean. I can't think of
another executive who'd tell me a thing.

385
00:31:14,338 --> 00:31:16,378
Like I say, I...

386
00:31:17,801 --> 00:31:19,759
I'll try.

387
00:31:19,888 --> 00:31:21,965
But I don't think there's much I...

388
00:31:22,099 --> 00:31:25,220
Look, uh, no troubles for either of us, Clete.

389
00:31:25,354 --> 00:31:27,394
Just... find out what you can.

390
00:31:29,401 --> 00:31:32,072
Trust me, Jonathan. You know you can.

391
00:31:32,197 --> 00:31:33,194
Sure.

392
00:31:33,992 --> 00:31:36,032
Well, sit down.

393
00:31:37,205 --> 00:31:39,245
Well, yeah.

394
00:32:06,748 --> 00:32:08,788
Thanks, boys.

395
00:32:10,712 --> 00:32:12,456
Good show, Johnny.

396
00:32:15,302 --> 00:32:17,343
That's the Houston stride.

397
00:32:18,348 --> 00:32:22,478
You boys wanna make this team,
play for Houston, you'll have to learn it.

398
00:32:22,605 --> 00:32:26,687
We, uh, pride ourselves
on being a power team.

399
00:32:26,819 --> 00:32:29,192
- That's right.
- We're power, we're mean.

400
00:32:29,323 --> 00:32:31,862
And that doesn't mean to say...

401
00:32:31,993 --> 00:32:34,830
...we like to have you
hanging back there on a rail...

402
00:32:34,956 --> 00:32:39,003
...in a fist fight, just fighting in section A,
when you should be in section B.

403
00:32:39,129 --> 00:32:42,416
I'm coming up to score
and you ain't in the right section...

404
00:32:42,551 --> 00:32:45,588
...it won't do us no good.
- That's right.

405
00:32:45,722 --> 00:32:47,965
Who's the, uh, two new catchers here?

406
00:32:48,100 --> 00:32:50,177
Right, uh, give me that ball.

407
00:32:53,900 --> 00:32:55,941
Don't, uh...

408
00:32:56,321 --> 00:32:58,991
...stick your hand in that gutter too quick.

409
00:32:59,116 --> 00:33:01,573
Wait till this ball comes down on the track.

410
00:33:02,914 --> 00:33:05,786
Don't get too anxious.
That thing'll take your arm off.

411
00:33:05,918 --> 00:33:07,413
Now the bikers.

412
00:33:07,546 --> 00:33:09,586
A biker...

413
00:33:11,343 --> 00:33:14,630
...might sacrifice
a little three-minute penalty...

414
00:33:14,764 --> 00:33:16,841
...run over the top of a skater...

415
00:33:16,976 --> 00:33:18,056
Uh-huh. Whoo!

416
00:33:18,186 --> 00:33:20,857
...if he feels that he's skating a little too good.

417
00:33:20,982 --> 00:33:24,435
So, we have a few methods
here in Houston. There's hundreds.

418
00:33:24,571 --> 00:33:28,701
One, of course, is to use this shield here.
Use your pads. Use what you got.

419
00:33:28,827 --> 00:33:31,615
Drive that arm in there,
keep your feet forward.

420
00:33:31,748 --> 00:33:35,118
Hit, move, you get away from the wreck.
Always keep your feet here.

421
00:33:35,253 --> 00:33:37,959
Don't come across in here.
You get all twisted.

422
00:33:38,090 --> 00:33:41,876
Or if a biker's sitting up nice and high -
a lot of guys like to ride high...

423
00:33:42,013 --> 00:33:44,801
...drag one off in midair. I hurt you, Blue?

424
00:33:44,934 --> 00:33:47,141
I wouldn't hurt him for the world.

425
00:33:47,270 --> 00:33:51,650
Now a... third method, and the one
perfected by a little friend of mine...

426
00:33:51,777 --> 00:33:53,569
...the swoop.

427
00:33:53,697 --> 00:33:56,782
Whoo! The swooper, that's me!

428
00:33:56,910 --> 00:33:59,865
Hang up on the rail,
use all the speed of the track...

429
00:33:59,998 --> 00:34:02,287
...come down and drop-kick a biker.

430
00:34:04,671 --> 00:34:07,246
Say... Excuse me...

431
00:34:07,383 --> 00:34:11,003
...you're, uh... you're not paying
a whole lot of attention, are you?

432
00:34:11,139 --> 00:34:13,678
What's this dude's name?

433
00:34:13,809 --> 00:34:16,646
That's our new speedball from Manila.

434
00:34:16,772 --> 00:34:18,730
Yeah, you know. That's Toughie.

435
00:34:18,859 --> 00:34:20,651
Come on up, Tough.

436
00:34:23,949 --> 00:34:26,239
- Oh, he's a big honker.
- <i>(laughter)</i>

437
00:34:27,413 --> 00:34:29,406
Say, why don't, uh...

438
00:34:29,541 --> 00:34:31,369
...you do me and the boys a favour?

439
00:34:31,502 --> 00:34:34,540
Since you know all there is to know,
we'd sure appreciate it.

440
00:34:34,673 --> 00:34:38,044
Why not give us a demonstration?
Show us how you made that big rep.

441
00:34:38,179 --> 00:34:40,967
Just skate around and, uh,
just... take me out, huh?

442
00:34:46,232 --> 00:34:47,513
Go get him, Toughie.

443
00:34:50,655 --> 00:34:51,604
Now...

444
00:34:51,740 --> 00:34:53,568
...eyes, use 'em.

445
00:34:53,701 --> 00:34:56,823
Don't lock your eyes in one spot.
This game isn't all in the muscle.

446
00:34:56,956 --> 00:34:58,155
Use your head.

447
00:34:58,291 --> 00:35:01,080
Lock your eyes on the target and keep...

448
00:35:01,212 --> 00:35:02,244
<i>(laughter)</i>

449
00:35:03,716 --> 00:35:06,837
Ears. Now, they're real important, too.

450
00:35:06,971 --> 00:35:08,169
<i>(laughter)</i>

451
00:35:14,023 --> 00:35:16,693
# <i>Tchaikovsky "The Sleeping Beauty"</i>

452
00:35:20,073 --> 00:35:23,408
Mm, if there's anything I love,
it's luxury centres.

453
00:35:25,915 --> 00:35:29,666
And when I get my privilege card,
I know what I'm gonna get me, too.

454
00:35:29,796 --> 00:35:32,169
- A secretary.
- What for?

455
00:35:32,300 --> 00:35:34,543
Are you planning on becoming an executive?

456
00:35:34,678 --> 00:35:37,349
Oh, I just need one. About this tall. Hee-hee!

457
00:35:37,474 --> 00:35:38,885
Yeah?

458
00:35:39,560 --> 00:35:42,017
Why don't you give it a rest?

459
00:35:49,617 --> 00:35:50,613
Hello.

460
00:35:50,743 --> 00:35:54,494
- Can I help you, please?
- Yeah. I, uh, tried to order some books...

461
00:35:54,624 --> 00:35:57,792
...and they said I had to appear
at the centre personally.

462
00:35:57,921 --> 00:36:02,086
That's right, this is our circulation unit.
Make your choice here or by catalogue.

463
00:36:02,219 --> 00:36:06,088
There must be some mistake.
The books you've ordered are classified...

464
00:36:06,224 --> 00:36:08,681
...and have been transcribed and summarised.

465
00:36:08,812 --> 00:36:10,306
Who summarises them?

466
00:36:10,439 --> 00:36:12,978
I suppose the computers summarise them.

467
00:36:13,110 --> 00:36:16,943
- What do you need books for?
- I just want to study up on some things.

468
00:36:17,074 --> 00:36:21,073
You could go to the computer centre
where the real librarians transcribe them.

469
00:36:21,205 --> 00:36:25,038
But we have all the edited versions here.
Anything I think you'd want.

470
00:36:25,169 --> 00:36:27,162
Well, let's see, then.

471
00:36:27,297 --> 00:36:30,668
This is not a library
and you're really not a librarian?

472
00:36:30,802 --> 00:36:34,054
I'm only a clerk, that's right.
I'm sorry about it, really.

473
00:36:34,182 --> 00:36:38,846
The books are really in computer banks
being summarised? Where is that?

474
00:36:38,981 --> 00:36:41,058
There's a computer bank in Washington.

475
00:36:41,192 --> 00:36:43,981
The biggest is in Geneva.
That's a nice place to visit.

